=============
  PACFORGE
=============

pacforge is a podman-compatible task-temporary container image and set of
scripts to build an Arch Linux package straight from a PKGBUILD file found in
the running directory, using a possibly customized makepkg.conf indicated at
container build time.

Dependencies listed in the PKGBUILD are installed automatically and unattended
before the build runs. The tooling is meant to be generic and reusable for any
PKGBUILD, not tied to a single package.

 1. MOTIVATION
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The initial use case driving this project is building coccinelle. The AUR
package for coccinelle currently depends on a long chain of AUR makedepends
whose build scripts do not build reliably.

pacforge's first concrete target is an adapted PKGBUILD for coccinelle that
resolves dependencies through opam instead, in order to bypass that broken AUR
makedepends chain entirely.

The problem should work for building any PKGBUID, however, and will be
maintained to be used with that in mind, since this is a constantly recurring
task for me.

 2. CONTENTS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~

makepkg-autobuild.sh:
	POSIX sh script that parses a PKGBUILD's dependency arrays, installs
	each dependency one at a time via pacman unattended, and then invokes makepkg. 

Dockerfile:
	podman-compatible Arch Linux image definition that installs
	makepkg-autobuild.sh and marks the image as an intended pacforge build
	container.

 3. USAGE
~~~~~~~~~~

The use requires 3 steps: 1) optionally, tune the build options; 2) build the
container image; and 3) run the container from the directory with the PKGBUILD
file.

3.1 Tune the Build Options
--------------------------

The `makepkg.conf` file contains the file installed at the container's
`/etc/makepkg.conf`. Theoriginal file is optimized for my own machine and local
preferences, and unless you have the same machine, they won't work for you.

The `makepkg.conf` file, however, is overriden at the `makepkg-autobuild.sh`
script (the container's entry-point) if a `makepkg.conf` file is found at the
running directory, meaning you can replace options easily before building.

3.2 Build the Container Image
-----------------------------

To build the container image, just type:
$ podman build -t pacforge:base .

3.3 Run the Container
---------------------

To run the container image, just `cd` to the directory where your `PKGBUILD`
file is and then call docker run with:
$ podman run --rm -it -v .:/workdir:Z pacforge:base

If a `makepkg.conf` is found at the running directory, it will override the
container image's default config.

 4. REPORTING BUGS
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Bugs and improvement suggestions are welcome. Open an issue at:
https://todo.sr.ht/~devlavender/arch-aur-contribs

